Adding new column(s) just because &quot;it makes it easier to ...&quot; seldom works out well. It has to be significantly easier when **ALL** uses are considered. Further have you considered combining the other tables columns to create an actual date or timestamp. However, sometimes there&#39;s away to have your cake and eat it too!  &lt;br/&gt;
Add your 2 columns, but make them VIRTUAL columns. That way nothing that currently processes the existing column needs to change and you get the date and time only columns. Downside: They are characters as ALL oracle date (timestamp) columns contains date and time components.

    create table  atable( atable_ts timestamp); 
    
    insert into atable values (current_timestamp);
    insert into atable values (current_timestamp - interval &#39;6&#39; hour);
    insert into atable values (current_timestamp + interval &#39;9&#39; hour);
    
    select * from atable;
     
    alter table atable add (atable_day  generated always as 
                                        (  to_char(extract(year from atable_ts) ) || &#39;-&#39;   
